base:bacteremia a type:Disease ;
    rdfs:label "bacteremia" ;
    prop:cause_in base:antibiotic ;
    prop:evoke_ base:sepsis ;
    prop:extractedFrom "Bacterial translocation (BT) followed by bacteremia is usually managed with antibiotics, but some cases remain refractory.",
        "Gram-negative bacteremia occurs more frequently in elderly populations (65 years or older) and is associated with higher morbidity and mortality in this population.[23]E.coli",
        "Other organisms that can cause community-acquired bacteremia include Pseudomonas aeruginosa, Klebsiella pneumoniae, and Proteus mirabilis.",
        "Persistent bacteremia can also occur as part of the infection process of typhoid fever, brucellosis, and bacterial meningitis.",
        """Resistant enterococcal species can cause bacteremia in patients who have had long hospital stays or frequent antibiotic use in the past (see antibiotic misuse).[20]
Gram negative bacteremia
[edit]Gram negative bacterial species are responsible for approximately 24% of all cases of healthcare-associated bacteremia and 45% of all cases of community-acquired bacteremia.[21][22]""",
        "Severe immune responses to bacteremia may result in septic shock and multiple organ dysfunction syndrome,[8] which are potentially fatal.",
        """]
Signs and symptoms
[edit]Low-grade bacteremia is typically transient and is quickly removed from the blood by the immune system.[5]
Bacteremia frequently evokes a response from the immune system called sepsis, which consists of symptoms such as fever, chills, and hypotension.[8]""" ;
    prop:include base:klebsiella_pneumoniae ;
    prop:manage_with base:antibiotics ;
    prop:occur_as base:meningitis ;
    prop:occur_in base:65_years_or_older ;
    prop:result_in base:organ_dysfunction ;
    prop:sourceUrl "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bacteremia"^^xsd:anyURI,
        "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Procalcitonin"^^xsd:anyURI,
